					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-lonewolf" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1300064); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1300064&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250575" alt="Dr Lonewolf" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1300064)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-lonewolf" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1300064); return false;" >Dr Lonewolf</a></span> <span class="odate time_1434843894 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Jun 2015 23:44</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2321228">
									

<p>I really enjoyed this. You are truly master of disjointed imagery. Skipping from moment to moment, only able to notice when he knows he's real.</p>
<p>This reminds me of something from a Shadowrun sourcebook. On the subject of Cybermancy, you are able to cram a ridiculous amount of cyberware into someone, enough to kill a normal individual. Technically the body dies during the process. They then bind the spirit into the body. Problem is, if the subject's mind wanders for too long, the spirit will go where they normally go, leaving behind a very expensive pile of meat. So they implant a stimulator into the memory centers of the brain, giving them a &quot;jolt&quot; every time the cyberzombie starts to vegetate.</p>
<p>&quot;Smith&quot; is in kind of a similar circumstance. If he doesn't remind himself he exists, he doesn't.</p>
<p>+1 for subtle existential horror crawling beneath the surface.</p>

							</div>

								
					
