					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hercules-rockefeller" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2314402); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2314402&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250575" alt="Hercules Rockefeller" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2314402)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hercules-rockefeller" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2314402); return false;" >Hercules Rockefeller</a></span> <span class="odate time_1462763078 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 May 2016 03:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2505550">
									

<p>That was beautiful.</p>
<p>I can certainly see why you're proud of this one, Decibelle. Having read this and a few of your other works, it's clear you have a gift for character studies - for making us sympathize with your characters by making us feel what they feel. Your portrayal of Mr. Smith is especially impressive when you consider how much of a non-entity (pun intended) he was in the original article. Also, I thought that bittersweet, cathartic ending was lovely, and your title is easily one of the most evocative I've seen on the site (and it only gets more beautiful when you get to the end and realize what it actually means).</p>
<p>I really don't have any nitpicks or criticisms with this one, but I do have a small question: what was going on during the containment breach at the start of the story? If there'd been a breach, what were those people doing having lunch in the cafeteria? Had they locked themselves in there <em>because</em> of the breach? If so, why did they unlock the door for Smith? (I know this has no bearing on the story, but I'm just curious.)</p>
<p>+10</p>

							</div>

								
					
