								<div class="title" id="post-title-2505558">
																		+55
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2005044&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250575" alt="Decibelles" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2005044)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;" >Decibelles</a></span> <span class="odate time_1462765696 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 May 2016 03:48</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2505558">
									

<blockquote>
<p>what was going on during the containment breach at the start of the story?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Truth be told, this was the only part of the story I didn't think through. I wanted an impetus for the rest of the story to unfold. If 1467 was wanting to escape before to see his family or at least figure out a sense of individuality (and those were hints I picked up on when reading the SCP), it was more plausible for me to have it happen during a containment breach than figure out a contrived way of making him escape on his own. It also sets up the scale at which he starts to fade; still there for the most part but rapidly deteriorating, versus already gone enough to slip out without the Foundation noticing.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If there'd been a breach, what were those people doing having lunch in the cafeteria? Had they locked themselves in there <em>because</em> of the breach? If so, why did they unlock the door for Smith?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yeah, they locked themselves in the there due to the breach. My take on it is a bit of a headcanon. If he's already being lost due to his ability, what people perceive he says and does might be different than what he actually says and does. They might hear someone banging on the door and the word &quot;Smith&quot; and possibly think it's other personnel, or a personnel named &quot;Smith&quot; and go to open it. I also tried to write it with the intention that the breach was either dying down or with minimal risk to justify an employee just opening the door there for someone else.</p>
<p>Thank you very much &lt;3</p>
<p>EDIT: Also, this is now a year old and at +55. I'm incredibly proud.</p>

							</div>

								
